column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While in the process of transferring freight from the breakdown area to the buildup area, three (3) 18-liter steel drums were damaged by the forklift.  Approximately 20 liters of free product were released and impacted the concrete floor.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel performed the cleanup using gloves, absorbent materials and shovels.  The cleanup materials were placed into a recovery drum for disposal.  The three damaged drums were placed into recovery drums pending shipper instructions.  The remainder of the shipment was forwarded to the consignee.  BAX Global, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.  No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS and freight bill were requested and received.  Please note that Bax Global, Inc. shall be named as the reporting party, as they discovered the release.
column169: BAX Global, Inc. will continue to remind forklift operators to watch the forklift blades while picking up shipments.

column168: During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, black liquid was noticed dripping from a trailer.  A response crew was notified and determined that the material was paint related material.  The trailer was taken to the dock and unloaded.  The contents were transferred to a suitable salvage box, along with the dirt that had been removed from the ground where the leak occurred.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound and returned to service.
column169: At the time the package was accepted for transportation, there was no evidnce of damage or leakage.  During the course of the response activities, it was discovered that the lid of an individual paint can came loose alloing a small amount of material to leak from the packafe and through the liner.  The individuals responsible for the preparation of this package have been re-instructed to insure all cans are placed upright within the container, that all closure devices are secured and that no sharp edges are present that could puncture the liner.  In addition, a suitable absorbent material is to be added in the event a package leaks and the liner is punctured.

column168: On September 8, 2010 the driver of a tractor-trailer operated by Hirschbach Motor Lines observed a liquid seeping from the weep holes of the trailer.    Local fire and hazmat personnel responded to the site, entered the trailer and conducted air monitoring.     On September 8, 2010 at approximately 11:30 am CDT, Hirschbach Motor Lines retained Cura Emergency Services (CES) to manage the environmental cleanup operations on their behalf. The CES incident manager contacted the driver to gain additional information about the release. Based on available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from USES located in South Haven, MS to assess the release and initiate corrective actions.    The crew from USES arrived on site, entered the trailer and continued air monitoring. Upon investigation, One (1) 55-gallon drum was discovered to be leaking from the bottom. USES personnel collected the free product from the floor of the trailer. The damaged drum was over-packed and re-secured for transport.

09/02/2010, 1102 HRS., ADVISED BY TRAINMASTER DENNIS SMITH THAT THE CARMEN WORKING TRACK MC-08, MEMPHIS, TN HARRISON YARD OBSERVED LIQUID COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OF RAILCAR ADMX 29071.  THIS CAR IS A RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED ALCOHOLS.  ARRIVED ON SCENE WITH DGR NORTON AND OBSERVED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  INSPECTED VALVE AND NOTED THAT THE HANDLE WAS BROKEN OFF AT THE VALVE AND COULD NOT BE PINNED IN PLACE.  VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  CLOSED THE VALVE USING A PIPE WRENCH.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, REQUIRING TIGHTENING BY TURNING CAP 3-4 TURNS.  LEAK WAS SECURED AND CAR OKAYED AT 1130 HRS.  LESS THAN 1 GALLON LEAKED AND EVAPORATED VERY QUICKLY.

column168: On 9/5/10 at 11:19 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Pinoca Yard in Charlotte, NC, discovered UTLX 200703, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide, Aqueous Solutions, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Evonik Degussa Corporation, was notified via CHEMTREC, # 2010-09-05-00030. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the release was caused by the breather assembly, continuous vent, device not secured to the rail car. The breather assembly unit and three of the four bolts were found on the working platform. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Stanley McSwain at 251-443-4443. HEPACO personnel re-attached the breather assembly and decontaminated the tank car. The leak was temporarily secured until a qualified repair facility could inspect the car per DOT regulations or the shipper could obtain a FRA Movement approval.     This incident did require a special switching move.   A QA 7.1 Non conformance report will be required.    Cause Code: 426  NARRI Code: 5(5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

AWB 027-9162-8806, 6 pieces, 135 lbs. was being transported to AS Flight 99, via freight delivery vehicle on September 10, 2010, around 11:20 AM.  One piece fell off the back of the vehicle and was crushed by a freight cart being pulled by the same vehicle.  Liquid spilled onto the drive-lane at SEATAC Intl. Airport, in the C-2 Gate Area.  Port of SEA FD ws notified immediately as was the Manager for Cargo Operations for AS.  POS FD responded immediately and assessed the situation.  Less than one (1) gallon of DG liquid was spilled.  Material was spread onto the spill, cleaning it up and spill was neutralized within 15 minutes.
column169: Memo was sent out immediately alerting AS Cargo Employees to ensure that when delivering any freigt, DG or non-DG, to the ramp to be loaded, it must be braced and secured.  Vehicle in question was taken out of service as a precaution and discussions are ongoing on if to modify the vehicles in question for better bracing.  AS has been operating these vehicles for 10+ years and has not had an issue with falling.

column168: On 09/03/2010 at 14:47 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Tilford yard in Atlanta, GA, discovered UTLX 662229, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. Crude Sulfate Turpentine, emitting an odor from the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Bowater Inc., and Chemtrec were notified, CHEMTREC #2010-09-03-00169. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found all eight manway cover bolts less than tool tight and the manway gasket was dry rotted. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Joann Combs 423-336-7236. Eagle/SWS replaced the manway gasket, re-secured the manway cover and wiped down the manway area. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  This incident does not require a QA 7.1 Non conformance report.    Cause Codes: 200/209  NARRI Code: 5(5+1+0) X (2+0) = 60
column169: Recommend that the manway gaskets are replaced when found to be defective.

column168: At 0545 on Monday, Sept 13, 2010 PTRA Trainmaster was notified that tank car TILX 100676 was leaking from the protective housing area in track 12 at PTRA Manchester Yard.  Rhodia and Shell Chemical Company were notified of the release and each dispatched response teams to asses and remediate the area.  Upon arrival it was determined that the liquid line was leaking from the cap and gasket area. After releasing the built up pressure on the car it was determined that two of the four bolts were tool tight the opposing two bolts were easily loosened when a wrench was applied with minimal force. Cause was determined to be a combination of pressure in the liquid line and insufficient tightening of two of the four bolts.  Oil Mop and two members of the Shell Response Action Team were on scene to secure the car and remediate the area. The gasket appeared to be OK but was replaced and the cap was secured. Excess product in the protective housing and on the sides of the tank car were cleaned off and neutralized with a sodium bicarbonate solution.  Solution was also applied to the product on the ground (less than one gallon) to neutralize the acid.  Area was cleared at 0920 hours.
column169: Shell Chemical Company is conducting an investigation to determine the root cause of the gasket/cap failure and pressure build up in the tank car.

53 foot intermodal container EMHU 242081 was noted by driver picking up container with solid product leaking from rear doors.  Container was isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, React Environmental, responded and found 1 of 17 plastic intermediate bulk containers had been damaged due to the load shifting within the container.  The non-rigid plastic intermediate bulk sack was loaded on a wooden pallet.  The movement of the sack on the pallet had cut the package material allowing the product to escape. During a routine yard check at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility, a van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was found to be leaking a small amount of material.  A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and found a drum had developed a small pinhole leak.  The trailer was taken to the dock and unloaded.  The drum was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum along with the absorbent material used to contain the spill inside the trailer and a small amount of stained gravel.  The trailer was cleaned with a suitable compound and returned to service.
column169: The drum was found to have a small pinhole leak caused by corrosion.  The driver picking it up thoroughly inspected the shipment and found no evidence of leaking at the time.  The drum had not rubbed against anything inside the trailer.  The age and condition of the drum apparently led to the release.    In order to help prevent recurrence, the shipper was advised of the incident as was asked to inspect their container prior to filling and while in storage to identify any containers that show evidence of deterioration and if found to take corrective actins before offering for transportation.

An end dump trailer arrived at the intended waste disposal facility. Although a solid ash material, this was a liquid that was leaking from the moisture content of the load.  The material was cleaned up from the containment area on which it was parked and the load entered the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: At the time the shipment was accepted for transportation, the load was inspected and no evidence of liquid was observed.  Throughout the course of the trip, load checks did not indentify any concerns with this shipment.  Upon arrival at the intended waste management facility, a small amount of liquid escaped from the rear seal of the dump trailer.  It is believed that residual liquid contained within the solid material being transported separated out and escaped between the rear door seal and the closure device.  Once unloaded, the vehicle was placed out of service and was taken to a local repair facility where a new door gasket was installed.

A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was parked at the ten day storage yard of the intended waste disposal facility.  During a routine yard check, it was found that a puddle of material had formed underneath the trailer.  A response team was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the trailer.  A plastic drum was split down the side along a seam.  The damaged container was overpacked into a suitable salvage drum.  All absorbent material used in the cleanup of the trailer was also placed into salvage drums.  The ground where the liquid had spilled was dug up and placed into cubic yard boxes for disposal.  The trailer was then unloaded and cleaned with a suitable cleaning compound.
column169: The area was experiencing excessive heat with outside temperatures nearing 100 degrees.  The temperature inside the trailer was quite warm.  It appears the drum built up too much pressure causing the drum to split.  The shipper was notified of the incident and will not fill the drums as full in the future.

A van trailer containing multiple shipments of hazardous waste was being unloaded at the intermediate truck transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating the shipments into trailers destined for different disposal facilities.  While transferring one of the drums with the drum grabber attachement of the forklift, a drum was punctured by one of the forks causing a leak.  The operator donned the appropriate personal protective equipment and overpacked the drum into a suitable salvage container.  The spill was cleaned off of the dock with absorbent materials which were also placed into the salvage drum.  The Louisiana State Police were notified and assigned case number 10-05410 to the incident.  At the direction of the state police, the East Baton Rouge Parish Emergency Response Agency was also notified but declined to make a report since no response was necessary.  The shipment was then loaded onto the trailer destined for the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The drum grabber attachement did not properly grab the drums, causing the incident.  It was taken out of service and sent to the vendor for maintenance and alterations.

column14: Hwy 17 North at the City Limit
column168: Driver of the Dufour Petroleum LP truck/trailer was delivering liquid gas to a customer when his pump did not work.  He called dispatch and was dispatched another truck and trailer to swap out with him to get his load pumped off. When the driver pulled off the trailer was not latched good and the trailer slipped off the back of the tractor as he was pulling onto Hwy 17 in Sulligent, Ala. The down trailer was pumped off onto the other trailer and delivered to the customer.  There was no release.  The dropped trailer was picked up by a wrecker and put back on the tractor and taken to the home office in Petal, Ms. after being inspected by the Alabama LP-Gas Board.  The trailer will go through a VK and IP inspction before putting back in service.
column169: The incident was discussed with the driver and he was retrained to double check the jaws around the fifth wheel to make sure they are latched correctly before moving the vehicle to prevent an incident of this kind from happening again.

column168: September 16, 2010: While performing a routine FRA Hazardous Materials Inspection (reference Inspector ID#H3407, Report 90, dated 09/16/2010) at Conrail's Burlington, NJ rail yard, NJ DOT Hazardous Materials Inspector J. Bowen noted exceptions to the following car, and phone-reported it to CR's Risk Manager, A. Richter:    SCMX 2364, load Environmentally Hazardous Substances Liquid, NOS (Alcohol C12-C16 Poly 1-6 Ethoxylate), Class 9, UN 3082, PG III, Marine Pollutant, with small residual product on top of the car appearing to have originated from the manway/manway nozzle.  Further inspection by CR, and REACT Environmental Services (contracted by shipper, Shell Chemical) noted four of six manway cover securement bolts not properly positioned for securement on the manway cover (cocked); and the manway cover gasket (garlock material) was deteriorated (noted to be improperly positioned with overlap to one side of the closed manway cover).  Inspector Bowen also noted the 4" bottom outlet closure cap was not even hand tight.    After verification with shipper over phone, gasket replaced with Viton manway nozzle gasket and manway cover properly secured, including the bottom outlet cap was resecured with an adequate tool.  Top of car decontaminated and wiped clean of any residual product and car okayed for forwarding to original destination.

column168: Spill was discovered when unloading a SL&C trailer at the dock at XLX.  The skid that contained the spilled product only had a few boxes on the skid and was stacked on top of another skid.  The skid with the spilled product shifted in transit causing the top skid to slide off and strike the wall of the trailer.  The impact caused the lid of a 1-quart can of paint to pop off and release paint within the box that was used to transport it. I APPROACHED THE SPILL ON THE SORT BELT WEARING ALL APPROPRIATE PPE.  THE PACKAGE WAS LYING ON ITS SIDE LEAKING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND OBSERVING THE DOT 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID STICKER LED ME TO THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  KEEPING ALL SOURCES OF IGNITION AWAY AND AVOIDING CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO BECOME AIRBORNE I ABSORBED THE SPILL, CONTAINERIZED THE PACKAGE FOR TRANSPORT TO THE DMP AREA.  USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS I DISCOVERED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS LOOSE CAPS.  THE SHIPPER OF THE PACKAGE DOES NOT ACCEPT RETURNED SALVAGE ITEMS SO ALL THE CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED THROUGHT THE DMP.
column169: BETTER PACKAGING PROCEDURES TO BE COVERED WITH THE SHIPPER.

column168: THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE FEEDER TRAILER ON THE FLOOR UNDER OTHER PKGS.  IT WAS NOTICED THAT A BLACK SUBSTANCE WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTON.  RESPONDERS DONNED PROPER PPE AND FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE, REMOVED THE PKG FROM THE TRAILER.  ONCE WE OPENED THE BOX TO SEE WHAT WAS LEAKING WE DISCOVERED THAT A 5-GALLON BUCKET WAS INSIDE. THE LID HAD FAILED AND WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK.  THERE WERE NO ORIENTATION ARROWS ON THE PKG OR ANY OTHER MARKING TO DETERMINE WHAT WAS INSIDE.  THE LABEL ON THE BUCKET WAS UNREADABLE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED TO CONFIRM WHAT WAS IN THE PKG.  THEY ANSWERED WITH "BLACK PAINT" AND AGREED TO SEND A MSDS TO THE UPS FACILITY HERE IN HOLLISTER.

column168: While unloading a trailer a carrier employee noticed dampness below the valve of the tote on the trailer floor.The employee then summoned the assistance of terminal supervisory personnel.After putting on the correct personal protective equipment, carrier personnel were able to determine that the IBC was leaking at the location where the valve is attached to the plastic body of the tote.  Not knowing if the threads on the valve/body of the tote were in sufficient condition to be tightenened, it was determined that the safest course of action would be to transfer the material into drums.   An emergency response contractor was contacted to perform this task.  The contractor transferred the material and cleaned up the trailer floor.  The cleanup materials were drummed and will be sent out for proper disposal.
column169: We have reviewed this incident with the shipper and they have indicated to us that  they no longer plan to ship this material in IBC containers. Although our driver  did not notice any leakage at the time of the pickup, we have conducted training  concerning inspecting containers before accepting them for transportation. This  training included reminding them that checking the valve area is a very important  part of ensuring that containers are acceptable for transportation.

column168: On 09/16/2010 at 14:40 hrs., personnel in Boyles yard in Birmingham, AL, reported to the CSX Public Safety Coordination Center that FRA Hazardous Material Inspector Kevin Cash reported to CSXT that UTLX 211203, a residue tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S., was leaking from the vacuum relief device (VRD). The car was bad ordered and sent to S yard for repairs by the shipper, Noble Americas Corporation, CHEMTREC was notified, report 2010-09-16-000167, and the shipper rep, Deb Dransfields 203-324-8555, called back to inquire about the rail car. The shipper contracted Eagle/SWS, a CSXT response contractor, to the scene. Once on site Eagle/SWS found that the leak had stopped. After further discussion with the shipper, they were contacting RESCAR to have the car inspected for a defective VRD.    This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause code: 457  NARRI Code: 2 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 28

AS THE DRIVER PULLED INTO THE STEPHENS CITY VA SCALE ON I-81 SOUTH HE NOTICED IN HIS MIRROR THAT THERE WAS SOME MATERIAL COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK. HE WAS DIRECTED BY THE PERSONNEL IN THE SCALE HOUSE TO PULL AROUND BACK AND WAT FOR THE STATE POLICE. HE DID AS DIRECTED AND THEN WENT ON TOP OF THE TANK TO CHECK THE WASH OUT CAPS. HE DISCOVERED THAT THE FRONT WASH OUT CAP WAS CROSS THREADED. HE TOOK THE CAP OFF AND PUT IT BACK ON CORRECTLY. THE STATE POLICE AND THE STEPHENS CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND SAW THAT THE MATERIAL EVAPORATED VERY QUICKLY WHEN EXPOSED TO THE ATMOSPHERE. SOME ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACE UNDER THE TANK AS A PRECAUTION WHILE THE TANK WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE TANK WAS SECURE AND CLEAN UP WAS NOT NECESSARY.

While at the UPRR Avondale, LA yard, tank car GATX 8727 was observed to be leaking from the bottom of the tank. The car was isolated without incident or injury. Cytek Industries, the consignee of this movement, dispatched tank car technician Mr. Chris Friloux. Friloux found the leak to be coming from the test-hole plug of the bottom washout. The plug was corroded and Friloux replaced the plug which secured the tank from leaking. The small amount of spillage was remediated with a soda ash solution.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A pungent odor was reported to be emitting from tank car SHPX 221049 located in the Beaumont Yard.  Response personnel from Oil MOP were dispatched to inspect the car.  Product was noted to be dripping from the B end liquid angle plug valve which was found to be open  turn, and with the liquid valve plug in position, hand tight.  Valve was closed, and plug was tightened which secured the car from further release.  The vapor valve plug was also noted to be in position, hand tight and was wrench tightened accordingly.  Upon proper securement, the car was released for transportation.
column169: Conduct proper post inspection of car prior to releaseing for transportation.

column169: We will review this event with our drivers at our next safety meeting and use this as a learning tool. We will stress the importance of staying alert in a construction zone and keeping off uneven roadway and or soft shoulders. We will also stress the importance of a pre trip inspection and inform everyone how significant it is to make sure that everything is properly fastened. column168: CN transportation department employee reported liquid product coming from the top and flowing down the side of tank car NATX 400648(L / LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS) during switching operations at the CN Markham Yard, East Hazel Crest, IL. The employee further reported that product was freezing on the side of the car and then evaporating off before hitting the ground. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated in track and area secured. CN's response team responded noting a free flow of product coming from the Safety Relief Valve, the flow stopped shortly after their arrival. Internal pressure was noted at 270+ psi / SRV set for 280.5. Upon further inspection of the car, the magnetic float gauging device was noted at 2.5" above the zero mark, designating the car was overloaded. Product reduced by 4,255 gallons, pressure reduced to 45psi, gauge noted at 21". Tank car released for movement to destination after twenty-four hours of securement. No further releases or pressure increase noted.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported UTLX 203060 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) with fresh product on its side shell. UTLX 203060 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with containment placed under UTLX 203060. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder along with contract responders inspected UTLX 203060. The responders reported product leaking down one side of the tank car's side shell and evaporating. No ground impact was observed. The source of the product release was at the liquid line's closure cap which was loose atop the fill port and had no gasket material inside this cap. Responders applied gasket material inside this closure cap and secured it after excess product inside the upper portion of the piping (the pipe area between the top quick connect fitting and the closed ball valve) was absorbed (removed). Response was concluded by 2030 hrs. MDT, 9/01/2010. All spillage evaporated.

column168: FPAX 931014 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported dripping product from its bottom outlet valve (BOV). column168: LTCX 1909 (DOT 113A90W tank car) in the railyard was reported venting product from its left side operating (equipment) compartment. LTCX 1909 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection by a shipper technician.  The shipper's repair/service technician reported that the 'isolation' valve mounted on 3/4 inch piping in line to the regulating or road valve (pressure relief valve) had vibrated loose via its mounting hardware (bonnet nut) and disconnected from the piping.  The valve disconnection from the piping caused product gas to escape. The technician reassembled the isolation valve with new bonnet gasketing and reattached this valve to the piping and secured it. No liquid product was released in this event. Repairs were completed at 1310 hrs. CDT, 9/18/2010.  Shipper seals removed (left side operating compartment) were PRAXAIR PLT 983 3134 and 983 3133; these were replaced by seals BNSF HAZMAT 001262 and 001268.  Shipper seal removed (right side operating compartment) was PRAXAIR PLT 983 3132; and replaced by seal BNSF HAZMAT 001261.

As the driver was initiating the unloading process, he noticed the pump discharge valve (V-7) was frozen up and would not rotate.  The customer operator assisting in the unloading process brought a steam hose and cracked open the steam valve at the utility station while the driver thawed the valve by applying steam to the stem/packing gland area.  After about a minute of applying heat, the valve handle rotated freely by hand, but was left in the closed position as the driver proceeded with the unloading procedure.  After engaging the clutch to start the pump, he began the process of opening the discharge valve while closing the recirulation valve to build pressure.  The pump discharge pressure initially climbed to 140-150 psig which is higher than the 125 psig target, so he turned the discharge valve handle again to ensure it was fully open, as he also began adjusting the VW throttle.  At that point, the V-7 valve blew apart causing LOX to spray into the trailer cabinet.  The driver ran around the side of the trailer and shut down the VW motor.  He then went to ther other side of the trailer to trip the emergency shutoff valve, but when he pulled the t-handle the valve would not trip, so he returned to cabinet to shut off the pump inlet valve.  After closing that valve the LOX flow ceased.  He then opened the manual vent to lower pressure on the trailer.  He secured the trailer for return trip to facility.
column169: Torque procedures for valve bonnet nut have been reviewed and communicated.  We have improved routing for actuation cable and ensured emergency valve operates reliably.  Review emergency response and will incorporate lessons learned into driver training.  We also communicated to all other sites with a safety flash explaining the incident, hazards to watch for, and corrective actions.

column168: WHILE AT CUSTOMER DOCK.  MOVING A TOTE ON FORKLIFT BLADES, THE TOTE SLID OFF THE FORKS, PUNCTURING THE SIDE OF THE TOTE, NEAR THE BOTTOM.  ALL OF THE PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF THE TOTE.  PER SHIPPER'S RECOMMENDATION AND AUTHORIZATION, A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR CONTAINED THE RELEASE.  THE TOTE WAS PROCESSED BY ER TEAM AND A LINED SALVAGE DRUM OF CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE DRUM AND TOTE ARE BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: BE AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS!  RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT.  CHECK BRAKES FOR PROPER AND SAFE USE.  IF ATTACHMENTS USED FOR FORKLIFT ARE IMPROPERLY WORKING, THEY MUST BE REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND BE REPAIRED OR TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE PERMANENTLY.  MAINTENANCE MUST BE DONE PROPERLY TO ENSURE SAFETY USE FOR ALL.  WHEN ENTERING OR EXITING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED OR STACKED ON THE FLOOR, ON A PLATFORM AND/OR HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS.  FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING.

column168: On 09/22/2010 at 03:44 hrs., Mr. Howard Dean, CSX Transportation Yardmaster at Parkersburg, WV, advised the CSXT Public Safety Coordination Center that a conductor reported a strong odor of chlorine around tank car PPGX 1704, a residue tank car of chlorine. CSXT notified the local authorities, NRC #954781, WV DEP #54138140 and Chemtrec #2010-09-22-00027. CSXT requested Chlorep team response via Chemtrec and dispatched Sunpro Environmental Services, Inc., an emergency response contractor to the scene. The shipper's,representative, Mr. Matthew Bond, and Sunpro personnel advised CSXT that the release was due to a slight vapor leak at the A end liquid line valve. Mr. Bond closed the valve 1/4 turn. He also discovered the plug for this valve was corroded. Mr. Bond installed a replacement, secondary closure plug for this valve.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.      Cause Code: 119  NARRI Code: 5 (4+10+2) x (2+0) = 160

column168: On 9/18/2010 at 14:30 hrs., FRA Inspector Robert Dedow found GATX 300472, a residue tank car of Waste Flammable Liquids, N.O.S., to have a vapor leak from the manway. The car was located in the CSX Manville Yard in Manville, NJ, however the car was transported by Norfolk Southern and Conrail. A CSX car inspector contacted emergency response contractor, Veolia ES Technical Solutions of Middlesex, NJ, Tim Ludwig 908-202-5674, who responded to the yard. It was determined that the shipper, Ashgrove Cement, used a rubber gasket that had broken down over time. Veolia ES Technical Solutions replaced the gasket with a teflon style gasket and secured the car for transportation. It was approved by FRA Inspector Dedow.    A switching move was not required for this incident.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI Code: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed APRX 3070 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the top fitting area. APRX 3070 was immediately cordoned-off in place awaiting detailed inspection from a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder. The responder reported that the liquid line valve was partially open (valve handle was 1/4 turn from being in the fully closed position) and its closure plug was not tool tight. The valve was closed and its closure plug was tool tightened 1 1/2 turns, which ended any further product release. Spillage on the tank shell was neutralized/absorbed with dry baking soda. Baking soda was also used atop product drips that impacted the ballast and ties under APRX 3070. Response was concluded by 1655 hrs. MDT, 9/20/2010.

column168: While being switched at the KCS Kansas City classification yard, SHPX 210187 was found leaking lading from a loose manway closure.  The manway closure was not tool tight.    KCS emergency mitigation services were activated to provide for special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, and regulatory reporting as appropriate.  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply as services require.    Note to report, item 27, amount in package, was estimated. This action required by preparer to facilitate data acceptance by defective DOT IT system edits. Specifically, this estimated quantity was required: (1)because the shippers only provided bulk quantities on shipping paper, as "1 Tank Car", per DOT requirements; and (2)because the DOT e-system requires data in this field to facilitate report acceptance.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. packages or closure defects such as this), shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFETY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column162: SR MGR - INDUSTRIAL SAFETY AND ENV

A LINED SALVAGE DRUM OF CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE DRUM IS BEING HELD PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: ADVISE SHIPPER - IMPROPER PACKAGING.  TOTES AND OTHER VARIOUS KINDS OF PACKAGINGS, CONTAINING CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE THEY LEAVE ORIGIN!  ALL TOTES MUST BE BLOCKED, BRACED, SECURED AND SHROUDED FOR ADEQUATE PROTECTION TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGING. USE LOAD LOCK BARS, STRAPS AND MTY PALLETS TO ENSURE LOAD IS SAFE AND SECURE BEFORE MOVING.  PAILS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING MTY PALLETS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  USE DECK BARS OR LOAD LOCK BARS PROPERLY AND SAFELY TO LOAD FREIGHT ON TOP OF!  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING, SIGNAGE STATING, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE SURE LIDS ON DRUMS ARE SECURED.

column168: The N&M Transfer driver as traveling east on Hwy 10 (Cottage Grove, MN) through a construction work zone where construction barrels were set up.  A blue mini-van was merging on to Hwy 10 from Jamaica Rd.  This vehicle abruptly cut in to the N&M Transfer driver's lane.  The N&M Transfer driver hit the brakes extremely hard to avoid hitting this blue mini-van.  This hard braking caused a freight shift within the trailer.  The N&M Transfer driver then exited Hwy 10 and proceeded to the 3M location on Innovation Dr., in Cottage Grove, MN.  Just before entering the facility the driver indicated that he then noticed by looking in his side view mirror, that liquids were coming out of his trailer.  The driver went to the 3M guardshack to inform that he had a spill taking place in his trailer.  The 3M emergency response team was notified by the guard.  3M's HM response team performed the entire remediation and decontamination of the trailer.  The cause of the spill was freight (metal stakes on a double-length skid) that was rear-loaded with no secure-ment in front of it.  When the brakes were hit hard the freight slid approximately 20 feet or more and crashed in to the two drums that were punctured.  The two steel drums were hit hard on their bottoms.  They were partially crushed.  Duration of the release was approximately twenty minutes. (An attempt to send photos will be made in a supplemental report).
column169: In this particular incident the freight that slid across the trailer was misloaded by our dock.  The driver was forcedt o work around it for most of his day.  The driver was told to never allow an open gap of floor space on his trailer without some form of blocking and bracing.  In addition, the drums themselves were strapped in place, however, they did not have a barrier in front of them (like a standing pallet) that would have prevented the metal stakes from puncturing these drums.

Driver immediately called his Operations Manager - John Redman.  The leak has been repaired.  John Redman, OM (404-695-7790) came to scene and repaired.  Approximately ½ gal of propane released. column168: A defective lid allowed herbicide to leak, drenching the pallets inside a truck trailer. This was contained using towels to eliminate the risk of migration.    Approximately 23 gallons of material was lost during transport. When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a drum that was leaking from one of the top bung openings. The bung opening had a protective seal over it so we could never verify the cause other that a loose bung. The leaking drum was placed into a recovery container and returned to original shipper as instructed.

When unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a tote that was slightly leaking from the top closure. A Level III Hazwoper person looked at the tote and after unsuccessfully trying to tighten the closure determined that it was a defective closure and held the tote in temporary storage until the situation could be corrected.

An eastbound BNSF train stopped on the main track after a passing BNSF train notified the eastbound train crew that an entrained boxcar was leaking a white powdery substance. The train crew reported that their train inspection revealed a placarded double plug door boxcar NS 469304 was leaking product from around the plug door closure. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was notified and traveled to the location where the train was stopped. The responder reported that one non-palletized flexible IBC (FIBC, a.k.a. nylon super sack) at the doorway had a hole in the upper portion of the bag (possibly caused by abrasion again the interior boxcar door or punctured by a fork lift tine) which allowed product to escape onto the boxcar floor and seep out from under the gaps at the bottom of the plug door during train movement. The responder plugged the hole in the FIBC with cloth material and also around the larger gaps at the plug door closure. Some spillage at the doorway was dispersed by high winds when the responder opened the plug door. Afterwards, the responder shadowed the eastbound train and reported no further spillage from NS 469304 during resumed train movement. A small amount of spillage that had been wind disbursed against the gage side of the rail and the ballast areas at the train stop location was later collected and placed into a 5 gallon sized container by a BNSF contractor for appropriate disposal.   On 9/21/2010 (approx. 1700 hrs. CDT), after NS 469304 arrived at the BNSF Springfield, MO railyard, it was reported leaking a white powder substance at the doorway of its plug doors. NS 469304 was carefully isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection. BNSF contract responders reported that one FIBC with a hole stuffed with cloth material (the same compromised FIBC previously reported herein from the 9/19/2010 incident) was the leak source of the material that had accumulated on the boxcar floor and seeped out from under the plug door closure.  The responders overpacked the compromised FIBC by placing it into another suitable FIBC. Spillage on the boxcar floor was swept and deposited into the overpack FIBC. Observed spillage around the boxcar's exterior doorway, on the ground and impacted soil (approx. 3 gallons total) was removed and then placed inside the railyard's waste container for later disposal.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFETY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFETY CHECKED TO ENSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED BY USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND/OR MTY PALLETS.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS.  RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  WHEN LOADING NOTE WHAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS LIE AHEAD.  HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON THE TOP!  USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT.  DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: On 9/5/10 at approximately 0900 hours, a tank trailer was about to be loaded via transload from a tank car of Sulfuric Acid. A seperate tank trailer had previously been loaded a few minutes prior. In between the two loads, the discharge valve attached to the top of the tank car was placed in the closed position to prevent any material from filling the hose until the next tank trailer arrived into the loading area. When it arrived and hose connection was being made, the hose plug was removed, yet some material had still entered the hose resulting in approximately 3 gallons of Sulfuric Acid to exit the hose onto the ground. No injuries were reported. Proper clean up was done immediately and later the material was properly disposed of as hazardous waste. It was found that discharge valve was faulty in respect to the handle being in the closed position, yet the internal ball was slightly in the open position to where it was not visible. Ball valve was immediately replaced so transloading could continue.
column169: All ball valves utilized for transloading operations have been inspected to ensure they are in proper working condition. All valves will additionally be inspected prior to all loading/unloading activities.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: A BNSF train crew reported GATX 200341 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product on its side shell in the railyard.  GATX 200341 was inspected by BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responders and was safely moved to an isolated area in the railyard for furtherance. Preliminary inspection revealed the leak source was at the valve housing area and product spillage was evaporating with no ground impact. A detailed inspection of GATX 200341 determined that the threaded liquid valve was loose on its threaded connection and its ball valve was partially open with its closure plug not tool tight.  The valve handle was bent in order to properly close the valve housing cover which resulted in the liquid valve not being in the fully closed position. The responders closed the liquid valve and tool tightened the liquid valve on its threaded connection (9 turns). The loose closure plug was removed and Teflon tape applied to its threads, reinserted and tool tightened. The valve housing cover was closed and resealed with BNSF seal numbered 3395758. Response was concluded by 1910 hrs. PDT, 9/24/2010. No further product release was observed from GATX 200341 during subsequent movements in the railyard.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: The driver arrived at delivery site and prepared his equipment to pump deliver product. The driver failed to inspect security of all delivery lines prior to opening discharge valve. Upon opening disharge valve, product began leaking from an unsecured dust cap on the other end of delivery line. Driver immediately closed discharge valve. Approximately 3 gallons was spilled onto concrete retaining are and was immediately cleaned. Total time from release to cleanup was under 15 minutes. The driver was admonished for not properly inspecting his equipment prior to unloading.
column169: Driver error was properly addressed and we do not expect any re-occurence.

column168: GATX47413 was discovered to be leaking from the manway area at approximately 1115 AM on Wednesday, September 29, 2010 by PTRA switch crews in Manchester Yard. Product was seen dripping from the manway down the sides of the tank car.  M&M Protection was contacted to respond to the incident.  They discovered the frangible disc was ruptured and the housing for the frangible disc was loose.  The housing was tightened to spec and the disc was replaced.  Product was rinsed and neutralized with a solution.  Less than one gallon of product was lost.
column169: Ashta Chemicals in Ashtabula, Ohio was notified of the incident and has started an investigation. PTRA will follow up on Ashta's action plan.

column168: After arriving on an inbound BNSF train in the railyard, DBUX 207810 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported with a product stain on its side shell which appeared to be emanating from its manway closure. DBUX 207810 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection. A BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responder inspected DBUX 207810 finding 4 of 6 manway securement swing bolts not applied (hanging) and the other two securement bolts applied were not tool tight. Intact shipper seal numbered 3964338 was removed from the manway to inspect the manway gasket condition. The manway gasket was found to be missing. A BNSF contract responder was called to install a new manway gasket. The responder installed a new suitable 21 inch manway gasket and properly tool tightened all manway securement bolts. Seal BNSF 015122 was applied to the manway closure. Response was concluded by 2200 hrs. MDT, 9/27/2010. Spillage around the base of the manway nozzle and the side shell of DBUX 207810 had cooled and hardened.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

HE GRABBED HIS SPILL CART AND DECISION TREE AND ATTAINED THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL, HE WENT THROUGH THE DECISION TREE WHICH LEAD HIM TO HIS CORROSIVE LIQUIDS RESPONSE SHEET. HE READ THROUGH HIS HAZARDS AND MADE SURE HE WAS WEARING ALL PPE BY PLACING THE SILVER SHIELD LINER GLOVES OVER HIS ORIGINAL GLOVES. HE THEN PERFORMED THE IN HOUSE CLEAN-UP BY FOLLOWING HIS RESPONSE ACTION STEPS. AFTER THE CLEAN-UP, HE PLACED THE PACKAGE IN THE SPILL TUB AND TRANSPORT TO THE PSC AREA HE THAN GOT ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS AND PROCESS THEM THROUGH THE DAMAGE MATERIALS PROGRAM.

9/27/10 Greenwood, LA City Police Officer witnessed the spill happen as our truck stopped at a light and immediately notified our driver (Daniel Modelist). The officer then contacted the following personnel who came to the scene:  Louisiana State Police HazMat Officer – Jay Hardy (Badge # 2157)    Caddo Sherriffs Office – Mike Viktaus  LDEQ – Ada LeDoux  TAS Environmental – Bobby McCoy  The Veolia truck was carrying a roll-off box container and as the driver stopped for a light, some of the liquid sludge material moved forward and spilled over the front of the box onto the road surface. There was not supposed to be any liquid material in this box as it had been drained at the facility before leaving, but apparently there was some that worked its way to the surface as the truck went down the road and as the truck stopped for the light it moved forward over the front of the box. Estimated amount of spill varies between 10 and 50 gallons, but entire spill clean-up, including absorbents and all other waste was contained in three, fifty-five gallon drums. All waste was contained, cleaned up and removed by TAS Environmental for disposal. No evidence of any migration or uncontained material, all waste was contained, cleaned up and removed by TAS Environmental for disposal.
column169: Better verification of the contents of the load before pick-up would have indicated the need for a different type of container, due to the liquid sludge content of the material.

column168: It was raining extreemely heavy.  It was hard to see the road.  I took the exit to the truck stop and found that the main lot was full so I went across the road to the west parking lot.  Numerous trucks were parked there also.  I saw a space by a fuel truck at the end of the building.  I went around back of the building (water was running heavy across the lot).  I turned to park and felt the trailer go into a huge pot hole.  The tractor was on the cement.  The trailer was on gravel.  I did not fell anything wrong when Ipulled the trailer out of the pot hole.  I parked for the night.  Normally I would take the dog for a walk and post the trip, but it was rainning so hard that I did not get out of the truck.  At 7:30 am I got out of the truck and found product on the ground.  The rear pipe had been knocked off and the pump was broke off.  The left rear outside tire was flat.  I made all required calls to report the spill.  Fire department and police evacuated the area.  Dyno Nobel were there to clean up.  Missouri DOT did an inspection and okayed all paper work.  OOS to replace pipe and repair the tire.  Returned the rest ofthe product to Barry Illinois and cleaned out the trailer.  I talked to Buddy at the plant who loaded the trailer.  He assured me that all valves were closed. I believe that the bad product that was left on my trailer for four months, by Dyno, damaged my valve.
column169: Dyno Nobel should not leave there bad product on trailer for a long peroid of time. The corrosive nature of this product will make rubber expand. This lot belonged to Flying J and has been a major problem for this town. Numerous trucks have had problems in this . Flying J had not put up any warning signs or maintained this lot. The police Chief repremanded Flying J and forced them to close off this area

A Univar warehouse employee was on a forklift and loading a sulfuric acid IBC into a trailer.  Two other IBCs were setting in the front of the trailer, a third one was placed in, and when a fourth IBC was being set down, the protruding fork on the forklift caught the valve of the IBC in front of it and broke it off.  Sulfuric acid spilled in the trailer and on the floorboards. The leaking IBC was moved into a containment area in the warehouse.  The spill was limited to trailer and dock area.  Univar employees washed off the truck completely inside, underneath and neutralized it with soda ash.  The truck appeared to be ok and they loaded him for the delivery.  The carrier subsequently filed a claim for replacement of trailer floor boards and other damage.
column169: The branch has conducted forklift refresher training with warehouse employees to review proper loading practices and IBC placement in trailers.

column168: Please note, Schenker, Inc. shall be named as reporting party only.  Schenker, Inc. was not responsible for initial preparation for transport, or palletizing shipment.                                                                           According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While on the pallet in warehouse at cargo facility, a leak was discovered.  Apparently, one (1), 21-liter plastic jerrican had been punctured by a nail on the pallet.  Upon discovery, area was isolated and hazmat guide was consulted.  As a precautionary measure only, facility was evacuated for approximately 4.5 hours, from time of discovery, until completion of cleanup.  One (1) employee sought medical attention at local clinic, was treated and released.  Returned to regular duties on 09/22/2010.      Ocean Blue Environmental of Long Beach, CA was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Ocean Blue Environmental applied absorbent material to the free product on the affected warehouse floor, recovered the spent material, and cleaned affected surface to remove residual product.  Ocean Blue Environmental also re-palletized the shipment, which was forwarded on to the consignee.  The cleanup materials, PPE, spent absorbents, and broken down pallet, were placed into one (1), 55-gallon recovery drum.  The damaged container was also placed into an overpack, pending disposition. Disposal will be coordinated in accordance with local, state and federal regulations.  Therewere no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Schenker, Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and hazmat safety to all personnel.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Conductor noticed leak on car on adjacent track as his train was entering the yard.  The conductor called our dispatcher who then called our in-house emergency responders.  CHEMTREC was then called along with local emergency responders.  The shipper was notified along with an Environmental Response Contractor who then off-loaded some of the excess material into a highway tank so the rail tanker would quit leaking since the rail tanker was shelf-full.  Since the tank was shelf-full, the pressure built up in the car causing the pressure relief device to release until product was taken off of the car allowing the pressure relief device to reseal.  We are not sure of the total time the release occurred but we do know it leaked for 2 hours.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: UTLX 211876 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from its manway closure onto its side shell during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and a BNSF Mechanical/Hazardous Material responder immediately inspected UTLX 211876. The responder reported no shipper seal on the manway closure and 4 of 8 manway securement bolts were either not tool tight or not applied. One manway securement swing bolt was not applied (hanging) and three were not tool tight. The responder properly secured and tool tightened the unsecured manway bolts. All spillage on UTLX 211876's side shell evaporated and no ground impact was observed.  Response was concluded by 1000 hrs. PDT, 9/20/2010.    Further investigation into the securement deficiency of UTLX 211876 uncovered the following.   UTLX 211876 was rejected by the consignee (BP West Coast Products, LLC in Seattle, WA) due to the consignee unable to remove the bottom outlet cap (BOC) on the bottom outlet valve (BOV) to unload UTLX 211876 at their facility. BP West Coast Products having limited track space at their facility and other concerns opted to return UTLX 211876 to the shipper's control to repair the stuck BOC. Since UTLX 211876 was not observed leaking product from the manway closure during its inbound movement to the consignee (BP West Coast Products, LLC) and the original shipper's seal at the manway closure was not present, it can be concluded that BP West Coast Products loosened the manway closure to prepare UTLX 211876 for unloading. After attempts to unload UTLX 211876 were unsuccessful, BP West Coast Products failed to properly secure the manway closure when they released UTLX 211876 back into transportation.
column169: Ensure that consignee follows their pre-trip inspection process to ensure all valves and fittings are closed and secure.

column168: On 09/13/10 at 06:00 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Barr yard in Riverdale, IL, discovered GATX 207972, a residue tank car of Ferric Chloride, Solution, with its protective housing cover open. The car was isolated and the shipper, Oklahoma Ferric Solutions Inc., was notified. Eagle/SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vapor flange assembly off of its nozzle. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Brian Woderzki, 219-728-9511. Eagle/SWS re-assembled the vapor flange assembly and secured it to the nozzle. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.    *Please Note: shipper contact Brian Wodetzki stated Oklahoma Ferric Solutions was recently sold to Kemira Water Solutions and referred all matters to Bill Tilker.       This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non Conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 322  NARRI Code: 5 (4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: UTLX 206415 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard was reported leaking liquid intermittently from the reclosing pressure relief device (PRD) atop this tank car. UTLX 206415 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting inspection. A BNSF contract responder inspected UTLX 206415 and reported the 165 psi PRD with a suspected broken valve stem which prevented the PRD from reclosing.  The responders enclosed the PRD with absorbent material and secured a containment cover around the PRD. Spillage on the side shell and around the PRD was cleaned. No ground impact from spillage was noted. Afterwards, UTLX 206415 was carefully moved to the nearby shipper's track in Oklahoma City for unloading. No further product release was reported during this movement.   After unloading UTLX 206415, the shipper secured the PRD in a closed position and was granted FRA-10100641 movement approval to send UTLX 206415 to a Union Tank Car (UTC) repair facility for PRD replacement and failure analysis. No further incidents were reported for UTLX 206415 during the BNSF transport phase.

On 9/28/10 at 18:53 hrs., personnel in the CSXT AACA Yard in Richmond, VA, discovered GATX 6189, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Norfalco, the shipper, and VA EOC were notified. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the gasket on the liquid line cap was deteriorated, causing the release. HEPACO replaced the gasket with like in kind material and decontaminated the car of spilled material. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. The Waterville, ME Fire department responded to the spill in an effort to contain it and determine the cause. It was determined that approximately 2 gallons of Resin material leaked from the drum, which was caused by fatigue and deterioration of the drum. Once the spill was contained, a local HM spill clean up vendor was contacted to overpack the drum and finish completing the clean up of the material in the trailer.

While at the PSC Container Services tank washout facility adjacent to the Slay Transportation Co., Inc,. facility in Cincinnati, Ohio, a leak was discovered coming from the tanker.  Approximately 25 gallons of free product were released due to a crack in the weld at belly of tanker.  Free product released to the concrete surface, and undercarriage of tanker.  PSC Container Services applied speedy dry to the free liquid.  Pettit Environmental of Cincinnati, Ohio was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Pettit Environmental applied additional absorbents to the free product, and wiped the contaminated tanker.  Pettit Environmental assisted in offload of the tanker, to a new tanker provided by Slay Transportation Co., Inc.  Spent absorbent material was containerized into a recovery drum, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a crack in the weld of tanker, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel, and perform routine maintenance on all equipment.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: A CTL truck was getting the water portion of a 50% dilution of Hydrogen Peroxide transfer. The peroxide had already been loaded on the truck and it was at the water station getting the appropriate amount of water for the transfer. After starting the water, the loader left the area and went to the maintenance barn. While in the barn, the loader became involved with activities in the maintenance area and lost track of the time the water was running. As the Foreman was doing verifications and MBWA, he went by the water station to check the water meter, since he did not see anyone at the station. When he got to the station, the truck was overflowing. He immediately shut off the water and removed the hose. He called for a code yellow, radioed the office and immediately began diluting the area with water per Hydrogen Peroxide procedures and the MSDS. It was determined that approximately 13 gallons of Hydrogen Peroxide was released on the asphalt.
column169: Root Causes - Failed to comply with the operational site-specific procedure for transfering Hydrogen Peroxide via dedicated metered pump. The loader failed to follow the procedure which states that the water must be added first in a dilution transfer. Loader failed to monitor the transfer.    Corrective Action - Retrained all terminal employees on the operational site-specific procedure and emphasized the importance of remaining with a transfer at all times. Emphasized loading water first in a dilution load.

column168: (A) A BNSF intermodal train derailed 9 loaded articulated intermodal (IM) flatcars on main track. The cause of the derailment was attributable to a broken axle on the first IM flatcar that derailed. Included in the derailment was IM container HJCU 905512 riding atop IM flatcar DTTX 750991. HJCU 905512 came to rest amongst an array of other IM containers. BNSF contract responders found non-bulk packages of cleaning solutions were damaged inside HJCU 905512 from load shifts caused by derailment dynamics. Two damaged poly drums were partially crushed or punctured by other lading during derailment load shift. Spillage of 'Aqua Soft' (laundry softener) remained inside container HJCU 905512. Damaged and compromised drums were either placed in overpack drums properly labeled or sealed in poly bags. Responders applied floor dry and lime to spillage inside HJCU 905512 which was collected and placed into 55 gallon disposal drums. Recovered waste in disposal drums were taken to a local disposal entity. Salvageable and non-damaged packages were repacked into another IM container for furtherance. BNSF contract responders found non-bulk packages of cleaning solutions were damaged inside HJCU 905512 from load shifts caused by derailment dynamics. Two damaged poly drums were partially crushed or punctured by other lading during derailment load shift. Spillage of 'Aqua Soft' (laundry softener) remained inside container HJCU 905512. Damaged and compromised drums were either placed in overpack drums properly labeled or sealed in poly bags. Responders applied floor dry and lime to spillage inside HJCU 905512 which was collected and placed into 55 gallon disposal drums. Recovered waste in disposal drums were taken to a local disposal entity. Salvageable and non-damaged packages were repacked into another IM container for furtherance. (A) GATX 46853 was involved in a derailment and came to rest on its side.  In the course of the derailment, approximately one cup of product was released from the pressure relief valve.  Investigation suggested that the valve was properly secured and the release originated due to a hydraulic surge experienced during the derailment.  No active release was observed as the valve had reclosed prior to the arrival of responders. The product was released to the ground below the protective housing and was remediated by removal of the contaminated soil. Waste manifest numbers for the shipment are:  002791157FLE, 002791141FLE, 002791140FLE, 002791139FLE. (B) CEFX 31556 was involved in a derailment and came to rest on its side.  In the course of the derailment, the contents of the gondola were released to the ground. The product on the ground was remediated by removal of the affected soil and the original product.

column168: Driver was loading through a LACT (meter) facility @ 5:13 a.m. - Employee was not in attendance of the process and overfilled the cargo tank.
column169: Designing and working with customer to implement automated overfill protection devices.

column168: The exact sequence of events is still under investigation.  We believe that while unloading, our driver, James Smith, discovered a release of LP gas from a flex pipe owned and maintained by Updike's Jerseyville Gas Service, 613 Maple Ave., Jerseyville, IL.  Our preliminary investigation shows that Smith manually closed all valves on the tank he was filling.  This initial release of LP gas caused an explosion.  After the explosion, an employee of Updike's Jerseyville Gas Service, Chuck Updike, reopened one of the closed valves resulting in a further release of LP gas from the flex pipe.  This secondary release of LP gas caused a second explosion.  We are still investigating the duration of the release.                                                                                                                     The package failure is contained within the flex pipe owned and maintained by Updike's Jerseyville Gas Service.  Although investigation continues, the failure resembles a burst or rupture.  No failure has been found within any of Huellinghoff Bros, Inc.'s equipment.  All failure is contained within equipment owned and maintained by Updike's Jerseyville Gas Service.  Further, none of Huellinghoff Bros, Inc.'s employees caused or contributed to the failure.  Huellinghoff Bros., Inc. originally reported this event by telephone on September 13, 2010 at 11:45 pm and was assigned case number 953920.
column169: We are continuing to investigate the exact causes of this incident and future actions needed to prevent recurrence.  At this time, we do not recommend any additional actions.  Our preliminary investigation shows that all failure was caused by equipment owned and maintained by Updike's Jerseyville Gas Service.

column168: 55-gallon drums were floor loaded in the nose of trailer and not properly protected (no dunnage at all).  Loaded directly behind them were wooden crates that had been turned sideways.  Since the crates were sideways, there were no openings to get fork blades underneath them.  When employee pushed his fork blades under the crates he went too far, puncturing the drum resulting in a 1/2 gallon spill which was immediately cleaned up.  The damaged drum and all clean-up materials were placed in a salvage drum.

On September 2, 2010, Swift Transportation contacted Emergency Response & Training Solutions (ERTS) to oversee environmental cleanup.  ERTS dispatched Morgan Environmental to the site to perform cleanup activities.  Morgan personnel arrived on site and collected the damaged containers and collected the released materials.  All contaminated materials were containerized for transportation and disposal.

column168: Truck and trailer loaded with 7900 gallons of Ethanol was E/B on US Hwy. 20 in the rain traveling at approximately 45 mph.  A car came up on his left side and entered the spray from his tires.  The car started to lose control and drifted to the right forcing the truck to move to the right to avoid a collision.  The truck drifted too far off the shoulder and drove down the embankment.  The driver attempted to drive the truck back onto the road but over-corrected and the truck and trailer rolled onto its right side, then rolled completely over coming to rest on its left side against an electrical pole.  The driver climbed out of the cab and called 911.  Though the tank suffered multiple dents there was no breach from the shell.  A dome cover had a minor drip which lasted approximately 4 to 5 hours until the Emergency Response Contractor arrived at the scene.  They placed a spill pad under the drip to absorb the product until the tank could be tapped and pumped out.  Illinois EPA was on scene and said there was no environmental impact from the Ethanol.

column168: While at sea, in transit from Spain to Port Everglades, Fl. the crew of the container vessel Veracruz Express V86W detected a liquid apparently leaking from a container on deck that contained the hazardous material noted above.The spill was estimated to be 10 -15 liters. The ship's crew using all safty precautions cleaned up the spill with rags and properly disposed of them. Reports to the NRS and COTP, Miami were made on Friday Oct 1. All available information on the dangerous cargo possibly involved were provided to the authorities.The vessel docked in Port Everglades 07:00 on Oct 3 and was met by representatives of the USCG COTP and both the Broward County & City of Hollywood Fire/Rescue Depts. Under supervision of the USCG the container in question was discharged to the dock. Properly outfitted firemen opened the container, sampled the leaking material and determined it was not hazardous. It was further determined that the hazardous material was safely intact in it's packaging (plastic drums). Both the USCG COTP and the fire departments were satisfied no release of dangerous goods had taken place and no further action was necessary.

column168: SPILL REPORT   Client: EE&G, Inc.   P.O.#: N/A   Generator: Southwest Convenience Stores   Date of Incident: 09/24)2010   Location: 101 North Main Street, Andrews, Texas   On September 24, 2010, Eco-logical Environmental Services, Inc. (EES) was contacted by EE&G (compliance and environmental consultants for Southwest Convenience Stores, LLC) to respond to a gasoline spill that occurred from a broken valve on a transport truck delivering fuel at the 7-11 convenience store located at 101 North Main Street at the intersection of North Main Street and Broadway in Andrews, Texas. The initial spilled volume was report to EES at 697 gallons. Prior to arrival, the Andrews Fire Department the Andrews Police Department, and the Texas Department of Transportation (TXDoT) responded as the result of a 911 call by store personnel. Upon arrival, Buddy Hobbs with the Andrews Fire Department updated EES site supervisor Aaron Pachihofer, P.O. regarding efforts to contain the spilL TXDoT and Andrews police had shut down the affected public tights-of-way where gasoline had travel west on Broadway for one block, then north on Northwest 1’ Street approximately V2 block. An Estimated 250 gallons fuel was collected in buckets and trash cans directly from the broken valve of the transport truck and was removed with a vacuum inick prior to the arrival of EES. At the direction of the fire department the spill on the public roadway was contained with sand noixnally applied to roadways during icy conditions. TCEQ Region 7 personnel, led by Environmental Investigator Karen Broeder arrived shortly after arrived shortly after EES.   After assessing the affected areas and conferring with TCEQ and TXDoT, EES determined that the affected material on the public roadway and on the store property needed to be removed for disposal. Using hand tool and a street sweeper, EES personnel removed the sand to a stockpiled area on plastic. A roll-off box was ordered, and the stockpile was transferred into the box once it was delivered. After all affected materials were placed in the roll-off box, it was transported to the EES office in Midland, Texas until the soils could accepted by a land fill for proper disposal.   The waste was taken to Charter Waste, a copy of the manifest is included.   Photos and a copy of the Xenco laboratory report (for waste characterization) are included with thisreport.   If there are any questions or COMMENTS, PLEASE do not hesitate to contact Eco-logical at 800-375-0100.
